INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jol3200','letter','1778-07-25','Providence','RI','US','John','Laurens','','George','Washington','','individual','','General Sullivan estimates the enemy\'s land force here at seven thousand. The state of their shipping, he informs me, is as follows...','ltr_jol3200.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jol3201','letter','1778-08-23','Newport','RI','US','John','Laurens','','George','Washington','','individual','','General Sullivan will inform your Excellency of the fatal determination of the Count\'s officers in a Council of War, as well as of the several remonstrances, and final solemn protest, made by the American Generals.','ltr_jol3201.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jol3202','letter','1778-09-02','Providence','RI','US','John','Laurens','','George','Washington','','individual','','The movements which your Excellency has observed at New York, the arrival of seventy sail of vessels in the road of Newport, the appearance of twenty sail off Boston, are circumstances which keep us in suspense','ltr_jol3202.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jol3203','letter','1780-02-14','Charleston','SC','US','John','Laurens','','George','Washington','','individual','','The day before yesterday, we had certain intelligence of the arrival of forty-five sail at North Edisto. A debarkation immediately commenced on Shnmons\'s Island; and an advanced corps, it is said, of five hundred, proceeded the following day','ltr_jol3203.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jol3204','letter','1780-03-14','Charleston','SC','US','John','Laurens','','George','Washington','','individual','','The enemy\'s present disposition of his force, and all his late operations, indicate a design to attack Charleston by a siege in form. To complete the in vestiture, he must introduce his ships of war into the harbour.','ltr_jol3204.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_jol3205','letter','1780-11-09','Charleston','SC','US','John','Laurens','','George','Washington','','individual','','On the night of the 1st instant, the enemy broke ground, and have been working slowly ever since. I scarcely know how to denominate what they have executed hitherto.','ltr_jol3205.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
